        <name>7.1.5.2 Distributivity of Matrices</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For the matrices \(A = {@mat1@}\) and \(B = {@mat2@}\), calculate:
&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;

&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(3(A+B) = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(3A+3B = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\((A+B)^T = \) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(A^T+B^T = \) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What do you notice about your answers to (a) and (b)? And (c) and (d)?&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the matrices \(A = {@mat1@}\) and \(B = {@mat2@}\), and are asked to find the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        3(A + B) &amp;amp;= 3\cdot \left({@mat1@} + {@mat2@}\right) \\
        &amp;amp;= 3 \cdot {@stepsApB@} \\
        &amp;amp;= 3 \cdot {@ApB@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@stepsApBt3@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@ta1@}
        \end{aligned}\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        3A + 3B &amp;amp;= 3 \cdot {@mat1@} + 3 \cdot {@mat2@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@stepsAt3@} + {@stepsBt3@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@At3@} + {@Bt3@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@stepsAt3pBt3@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@ta1@}
        \end{aligned}\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        (A + B)^T &amp;amp;= \left({@mat1@} +  {@mat2@}\right)^T \\
        &amp;amp;= {@stepsApB@}^T \\
        &amp;amp;= {@ApB@}^T \\
        &amp;amp;= {@ta2@}
        \end{aligned}\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned}
        A^T + B^T &amp;amp;= {@mat1@}^T + {@mat2@}^T \\
        &amp;amp;= {@AT@} + {@BT@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@stepsATpBT@} \\
        &amp;amp;= {@ta2@}
        \end{aligned}\]
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you probably have noticed, the answers to (a) and (b) are equal, as are the answers to (c) and (d). This is no coincidence, since \(3(A + B) = 3A + 3B\) and \((A+B)^T = A^T + B^T\) by distributivity of scalar multiplication and transpose over addition.&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
